kets.businessinsider.com%2Findex%2Fs%26amp%3Bp_500%5C%22%3ES%26amp%3BP%20500%3C%2Fa%3E%20is%20trading%208%25%20higher%20today%20than%20before%20the%20Federal%20Reserve%20began%20its%20flurry%20of%20interest-rate%20hikes%20last%20spring.%20That's%20surprising%20for%20a%20bunch%20of%20reasons%20%E2%80%94%20but%20perhaps%20it%20shouldn't%20be.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20benchmark%20US%20stock%20index%20closed%20at%204%2C720%20points%20on%20Thursday%2C%20compared%20to%204%2C358%20points%20on%20March%2016%20last%20year%2C%20the%20day%20before%20the%20Fed%20began%20its%20latest%20hiking%20cycle.%20The%20US%20central%20bank%20went%20on%20to%20raise%20its%20benchmark%20rate%20from%20nearly%20zero%20to%20upwards%20of%205.25%25%20%E2%80%94%20a%2022-year%20high%20%E2%80%94%20in%20the%20space%20of%20just%20over%2016%20months.%20It%20has%20held%20rates%20steady%20since%20July.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20Fed%20hiked%20in%20response%20to%20a%20historic%20spike%20in%20inflation.%20Annualized%20price%20growth%20hit%20a%2040-year%20high%20of%20over%209%25%20last%20summer%2C%20far%20outpacing%20the%20central%20bank's%202%25%20target.%20Higher%20rates%20encourage%20saving%20over%20spending%20and%20make%20borrowing%20more%20expensive%2C%20which%20tends%20to%20temper%20overall%20demand%20in%20the%20economy%20and%20slow%20the%20pace%20of%20price%20increases.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20rate%20hikes%20work%20in%20part%20by%20squeezing%20consumers%2C%20forcing%20them%20to%20allocate%20more%20of%20their%20monthly%20incomes%20toward%20the%20bigger%20payments%20due%20on%20their%20credit%20cards%2C%20car%20loans%2C%20mortgages%2C%20and%20other%20debts.%20American%20households%20have%20also%20faced%20soaring%20food%2C%20fuel%2C%20and%20rent%20costs%2C%20which%20have%20stretched%20their%20budgets%20even%20more.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBetween%20inflation%20in%20living%20expenses%20and%20higher%20debt%20costs%2C%20consumers%20have%20been%20left%20with%20less%20disposable%20income%20to%20spend%20on%20goods%20and%20services%20produced%20by%20companies%2C%20hurting%20sales.%20Corporations%20have%20also%20seen%20their%20costs%20and%20interest%20payments%20jump%2C%20pinching%20their%20profit%20margins.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EA%20company's%20shares%20are%20generally%20valued%20at%20a%20multiple%20to%20its%20future%20earnings%2C%20meaning%20if%20investors%20expect%20its%20profits%20to%20grow%20less%20quickly%20or%20even%20shrink%2C%20its%20stock%20price%20should%20come%20down.%20Stocks%20also%20become%20relatively%20less%20appealing%20to%20investors%20when%20rates%20rise%2C%20as%20the%20returns%20from%20safe%20assets%20like%20savings%20accounts%20and%20government%20bonds%20increase.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EStocks%20are%20valued%20based%20on%20their%20future%20cash%20flows%2C%20so%20if%20investors%20see%20companies%20struggling%20to%20raise%20prices%20to%20protect%20their%20profit%20margins%20from%20inflation%2C%20and%20spending%20more%20to%20cover%20their%20debt%20costs%20each%20month%2C%20they'll%20reduce%20their%20cash-flow%20forecasts%20and%20assign%20a%20lower%20value%20to%20their%20shares%20today.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EMoreover%2C%20hiking%20interest%20rates%20can%20slow%20the%20economy%20so%20much%20that%20it%20enters%20a%20prolonged%20downturn%20or%20recession.%20Consumers%20tend%20to%20pull%20back%20on%20spending%20and%20investors%20flee%20to%20safety%20when%20they%20fear%20economic%20pain%2C%20providing%20another%20reason%20why%20stocks%20tend%20to%20suffer%20when%20rates%20increase.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBetween%20elevated%20inflation%2C%20a%20rapid-fire%20series%20of%20rate%20hikes%2C%20and%20the%20increased%20risk%20of%20a%20recession%2C%20there%20are%20clear%20pressures%20on%20stocks%20today.%20On%20the%20other%20hand%2C%20inflation%20has%20cooled%20to%20below%204%25%20in%20recent%20months%2C%20the%20US%20economy%20grew%20strongly%20in%20the%20third%20quarter%2C%20and%20the%20Fed%20signaled%20this%20week%20that%20it%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Finterest-rates-fed-pauses